Time Continues to Operate

In 一个人的村庄, time does not pass through human experience; it accumulates in dust, wind, and shadow. The narrative does not begin with an event but with a duration already underway. By the time a sentence acknowledges perception, the light has long settled on the wall, the animal has crossed the yard, and the afternoon has completed part of its work. The human figure arrives late—not as origin, but as delay.

This delay is not thematic; it is structural. The prose repeatedly redistributes agency away from intention and toward environment. Verbs detach from psychological motive and reattach to material processes: wind moves, snow presses, walls retain warmth. The grammar does not dramatize human consciousness; it records temporal sedimentation. What appears as slowness is in fact a reallocation of narrative authority.

When read alongside the system of misdirected messages in 捎话, the pattern becomes more legible. Information does not fail because humans misunderstand it; rather, transmission unfolds within a temporal field that exceeds intention. Meaning lags behind its own articulation. The narrative voice withholds summary not as stylistic modesty but as operational principle. Interpretation is structurally deferred.

In this sense, Liu Liangcheng does not merely slow narrative time; he reorganizes its hierarchy. Time is no longer measured by plot progression but by environmental continuation. The village is not a setting. It is a low-frequency system in which human urgency cannot maintain dominance. What persists is not memory, but duration itself.
Across a representative corpus drawn from 一个人的村庄 and early short prose pieces, syntactic distribution reveals a measurable withdrawal of explanatory authority. Sentences that explicitly assign causality or interpret experience remain statistically marginal. Instead, clauses are frequently organized around environmental continuity: temporal markers such as “already,” “still,” and “again” outnumber causal connectors. More strikingly, non-human subjects dominate verbal initiation. Wind, dust, animals, and seasonal processes repeatedly occupy the grammatical position conventionally reserved for human intention. When human agents do appear, they often enter the sentence belatedly, as recipients rather than initiators of action. This pattern is not reducible to descriptive style. It produces a structural asymmetry in which perception follows process.

A similar configuration becomes intensified in 捎话. The frequency of interpretive closure—sentences that resolve uncertainty, provide motive, or synthesize event—declines even further. Instead, the narrative accumulates incomplete transmissions, postponed recognitions, and temporal disjunctions. Crucially, this deferral does not generate suspense in the conventional sense. Rather, it redistributes epistemic control away from both narrator and reader. The text withholds the stabilization of meaning, allowing duration to function as the primary organizing principle. In this structure, misunderstanding is not an obstacle to communication; it is the operational condition under which narrative unfolds.
To account for this configuration, I propose the concept of Temporal Autonomy Narrative. In this model, time does not function as background, sequence, or experiential container. Instead, it operates as an autonomous structuring force that precedes and exceeds human cognition. Narrative progression is no longer governed by intention, conflict, or psychological development, but by the continuation of environmental processes. Human presence becomes episodic and discontinuous, appearing only as a local interruption within ongoing duration. The significance of this shift lies in its structural implications: agency migrates from subject to temporality itself. What advances the narrative is not decision but continuation.
This reconfiguration is inseparable from what may be termed Environmental Agency Syntax. At the level of grammar, Liu Liangcheng’s prose systematically redistributes the position of initiation. Environmental elements—wind, dust, animals, seasonal rhythms—occupy the syntactic site of action, while human actors are repositioned as receivers of temporal pressure. Such patterns exceed stylistic preference. They produce a persistent inversion of anthropocentric hierarchy embedded in language. Rather than representing a world in which humans are displaced, the prose enacts displacement through sentence construction. In this sense, the narrative does not describe decentering; it performs it.
The critical consequence of these mechanisms is that meaning is not suspended but structurally delayed. Duration becomes the medium through which interpretation emerges, if it emerges at all. This distinguishes Liu Liangcheng’s work from both conventional slow writing and theoretical posthumanism. In texts such as 捎话, misunderstanding is not thematic but operational: communication unfolds within temporal fields that remain indifferent to human urgency. Time continues to operate regardless of comprehension. Narrative thus becomes an index of temporal autonomy rather than human experience.
The implications of this structure extend beyond decentering. It becomes possible to formulate a more radical claim: Liu Liangcheng’s narrative does not merely displace the human; it suspends the necessity of the human for narrative continuation. Duration, environmental process, and material persistence generate coherence independently of subjective experience. Human presence neither guarantees meaning nor determines progression. Instead, narrative stability emerges from temporal endurance.
This distinction separates Liu Liangcheng from dominant formulations of posthuman thought. In theoretical discourse, including the work of Donna Haraway and Timothy Morton, the human remains structurally required as observer, participant, or ethical interlocutor. Even when decentered, the human continues to function as a mediating node. By contrast, in texts such as 一个人的村庄, environmental processes neither seek recognition nor depend on interpretive frameworks. Wind continues to move, animals continue to act, seasons continue to reorganize space, regardless of perceptual registration. The narrative does not stage relational entanglement; it records ongoing operations.
This shift also redefines narrative tension. In conventional structures, uncertainty arises from incomplete knowledge or obstructed intention. In Liu Liangcheng’s prose, tension emerges from temporal indifference. The world does not resist the human; it proceeds without reference to human urgency. Miscommunication in 捎话 therefore should not be read as epistemological crisis but as structural confirmation. Messages fail not because they are distorted, but because temporal continuation renders precision unnecessary. Communication becomes one process among many, rather than the organizing principle of narrative.
The theoretical consequence is that narrative no longer requires a human-centered horizon. What persists is not subjectivity, but operation. Time continues to act, and narrative follows its movement.
This perspective allows for a final and more radical formulation. Liu Liangcheng does not write about time. He writes from the position of time. The distinction is decisive. To write about time presupposes a stable observing subject, for whom temporality remains an object of reflection, memory, or philosophical inquiry. In Liu Liangcheng’s prose, such a position is systematically withdrawn. Temporal processes do not appear as themes or problems; they function as the condition of narrative enunciation itself.
From this vantage, narration no longer originates in human perception. Instead, perception emerges as one delayed registration among many ongoing processes. The sentence does not move forward because a subject chooses to narrate; it continues because duration continues. The grammatical surface therefore resembles an observational record, yet its operative center is displaced. What appears as description is in fact alignment. Language adjusts itself to temporal persistence rather than imposing structure upon it.
This shift clarifies why human experience in texts such as 一个人的村庄 often seems secondary, fragmentary, or incomplete. Memory does not organize time; it accumulates within it. Similarly, in 捎话, communication fails to stabilize narrative because stabilization would require a privileged human vantage point. Instead, temporal continuation absorbs error, delay, and loss as ordinary operations. The narrative voice does not resist this absorption. It persists within it.
The theoretical implications extend beyond both narratology and posthuman discourse. If narrative can be produced from the position of time, then agency no longer coincides with subjectivity, and coherence no longer depends on intentional design. Narrative becomes a mode of temporal self-articulation. The human appears not as origin or destination, but as a transient confTo situate Liu Liangcheng within world literature requires a shift in critical perspective. The question is not how a rural Chinese writer enters global circulation, nor how local experience becomes legible within transnational frameworks. Rather, his work suggests a temporal paradigm shift in narrative itself. What is at stake is not representation, but orientation.
In dominant models of modern and contemporary world literature, narrative transformation has often been aligned with spatial expansion: globalization, migration, translation, and circulation. From Johann Wolfgang von Goethe’s early reflections on Weltliteratur to contemporary discussions shaped by David Damrosch and Franco Moretti, the central problem has remained one of movement across cultural and geographic boundaries. Even when temporal concerns emerge, they are frequently subordinated to historical modernity, development, or acceleration. Liu Liangcheng’s prose, by contrast, reorganizes narrative at the level of temporal ontology. The village in 一个人的村庄 does not function as a site of cultural authenticity or resistance to modernization. It operates as a low-frequency temporal field in which global acceleration loses structural authority.
This shift carries methodological consequences. If narrative can be generated from the position of time rather than the position of space, then the comparative framework of world literature must be recalibrated. Liu Liangcheng’s work invites comparison not through shared themes or historical contexts, but through temporal configurations. In this regard, his prose stands in productive tension with modernist temporal fragmentation, exemplified in Ulysses, and with institutional temporality in The Trial. Where Joyce intensifies subjective temporality and Kafka exposes bureaucratic delay, Liu Liangcheng displaces the necessity of subjective or institutional time altogether. Duration persists without psychological interiority or systemic constraint.
Such a reorientation suggests that world literature may no longer be organized primarily around the circulation of texts, but around shifts in temporal regimes. From this perspective, Liu Liangcheng marks a transition from narrative structured by historical modernity to narrative structured by environmental duration. His work therefore does not merely contribute to global literary diversity; it alters the conditions under which narrative coherence becomes possible. The temporal autonomy enacted in texts such as 捎话 indicates a broader transformation: literature no longer records the experience of time, but becomes a medium through which time articulates itself across cultures.

时间自运行
在《一个人的村庄》中，时间并不通过人的经验流逝；它在尘土、风与影子中累积。叙事并非从事件开始，而是从已经在进行的延续中展开。当句子开始承认感知时，光早已落在墙上，动物已经穿过院子，下午也已完成了它的部分工作。人的身影总是迟到——不是起点，而是延宕。
这种延宕并非主题性的，而是结构性的。散文不断将能动性从意图转移到环境。动词从心理动机中脱离，并重新附着于物质过程：风在移动，雪在压迫，墙在留存温度。语法并不戏剧化人的意识，而是记录时间的沉积。看似的缓慢实际上是叙事权力的再分配。
与《捎话》中错置信息的系统并读时，这一模式变得更为清晰。信息并非因人类误解而失败；相反，传递在超出意义的时间场中展开。意义落后于自身的表达。叙述声音之所以不进行总结，并非出于风格上的克制，而是作为一种运作原则。解释在结构上被推迟。
从这一意义上说，刘亮程并非仅仅放慢叙事时间；他重组了其层级。时间不再由情节推进来计量，而由环境的持续来计量。村庄不是背景，而是一种低频率的系统，在其中人类的紧迫性无法维持主导地位。持续的不是记忆，而是延续本身。
在从《一个人的村庄》及早期短篇散文中抽取的代表性语料中，句法分布呈现出一种可测量的解释权撤离。明确赋予因果或解释经验的句子在统计上保持边缘地位。相反，从句常围绕环境的连续性组织：“已经”“仍然”“再次”等时间标记的出现频率高于因果连接词。更为显著的是，非人主体主导了动词的发起位置。风、尘土、动物与季节性过程反复占据传统上属于人类意图的语法位置。当人类行动者出现时，他们往往在句子中迟到，作为接受者而非发起者。这一模式并非可归结为描写风格，而是生成了一种结构性的不对称：感知跟随过程。
在《捎话》中，这一结构进一步强化。解释性收束——即解决不确定性、提供动机或综合事件的句子——出现频率进一步下降。叙事转而累积未完成的传递、被推迟的识认与时间错位。关键在于，这种延宕并不产生传统意义上的悬念，而是将认识论控制从叙述者与读者处移走。文本拒绝意义的稳定，使延续成为主要的组织原则。在这一结构中，误解并非沟通的障碍，而是叙事展开的运作条件。
为描述这一结构，我提出“时间自主叙事”（Temporal Autonomy Narrative）的概念。在这一模型中，时间不再作为背景、顺序或经验容器，而是作为一种先于并超出人类认知的自主结构力量。叙事推进不再由意图、冲突或心理发展所支配，而由环境过程的持续所支配。人的出现变得片段化、不连续，只是持续时间中的局部性打断。这一转向的意义在于其结构后果：能动性从主体迁移至时间本身。推动叙事的不是决定，而是延续。
这一重组与可称为“环境能动句法”（Environmental Agency Syntax）的机制不可分割。在句法层面，刘亮程的散文系统性地重新分配发起位置。环境元素——风、尘土、动物、季节节律——占据动作的句法位置，而人类行动者被重新定位为时间压力的接受者。这些模式超越了风格偏好，生成了语言内部对人类中心主义层级的持续反转。散文并非描写一个人类被置后的世界，而是通过句子结构执行置后。在此意义上，叙事并不描述去中心化；它实施去中心化。
这一机制的批评后果在于：意义不是被悬置，而是被结构性延迟。延续成为解释得以出现的媒介——如果它出现的话。这使刘亮程的作品区别于传统的“慢写作”与理论性的后人类主义。在《捎话》等文本中，误解并非主题，而是运作方式：沟通在对人类紧迫性保持冷漠的时间场中展开。时间无论理解与否都持续运作。叙事因而成为时间自主性的指数，而非人类经验的记录。
这一结构的含义超越了去中心化本身。可以提出一个更激进的判断：刘亮程的叙事不仅仅将人类移位，而是暂停了叙事延续对人的必要性。延续、环境过程与物质持存独立于主观经验生成连贯性。人的存在既不保证意义，也不决定推进。叙事的稳定性来自时间的耐久。
这一差异使刘亮程与主流后人类理论分离。在理论话语中，包括 Donna Haraway 与 Timothy Morton 的工作，人类仍然在结构上被要求作为观察者、参与者或伦理节点。即便被去中心化，人类仍作为中介存在。相反，在《一个人的村庄》等文本中，环境过程既不寻求被识认，也不依赖解释框架。风继续移动，动物继续行动，季节继续重组空间，无论是否被感知。叙事并不呈现关系纠缠，而是记录持续运作。
这一转向也重新定义了叙事张力。在传统结构中，不确定性来自知识的不完整或意图的受阻。在刘亮程的散文中，张力来自时间的冷漠。世界并不抵抗人类；它只是无视人类的紧迫性而继续。因而，《捎话》中的误传不应被视为认识论危机，而应被视为结构确认。信息之所以失败，不是因为被扭曲，而是因为时间的持续使精确变得不必要。沟通只是众多过程之一，而非叙事的组织原则。
理论上的结果是：叙事不再需要以人为中心的地平线。持续的不是主体性，而是运作。时间继续行动，叙事跟随其运动。
这一视角允许一个最终且更为根本的判断：刘亮程不是在写“关于时间”的作品，而是在“时间的位置上”写作。这一区别具有决定性。写“关于时间”预设了一个稳定的观察主体，使时间成为反思、记忆或哲学探问的对象。在刘亮程的散文中，这一主体位置被系统性撤除。时间过程不作为主题或问题出现，而作为叙事发声的条件。
从这一视角出发，叙述不再源自人的感知；相反，感知只是众多持续过程中的一个延迟记录。句子之所以向前推进，不是因为主体选择叙述，而是因为延续继续。句法表面因此类似观察记录，但其运作中心已被移位。看似的描写实际上是对齐：语言调整自身以适应时间的持续，而非对其施加结构。
这一转向解释了为何《一个人的村庄》等文本中的人类经验常显得次要、片段化或不完整。记忆并不组织时间；它在时间中累积。同样，在《捎话》中，沟通无法稳定叙事，因为稳定性需要一个被特权化的人类视角。相反，时间的持续将错误、延迟与丢失吸纳为普通运作。叙述声音并不抵抗这种吸纳，而是在其中持续。
这一理论含义超越了叙事学与后人类论述。如果叙事可以从时间的位置生成，那么能动性不再与主体性重合，连贯性也不再依赖意图性设计。叙事成为时间自我表达的一种方式。人类不再作为起点或终点，而只是持续时间中的一个瞬时构形。

